    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-14T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-14T03:00:00-05:00" n="362"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d362">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115 Standard Vacuum Oil Company/4:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Tsingtao</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sokobin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tsingtao</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-14T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 14, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 14—10:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>With reference to my telegram of September 11, 5 p.m.,<note n="28"
                        xml:id="d362fn28">Not printed.</note> junks destroyed by Japanese warship
                    carried no oil. However, shipment <pb facs="0335" n="327" xml:id="pg_327"/> of
                    American oil on 5 junks arrived safely with exception of 114 cases of kerosene
                    which were confiscated by a Japanese warship.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Nanking, Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sokobin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
